<br>
Indeed.  And quite a logical inferrence indeed.  Examine the language again.  Notice the placement of the word &quot;Yet.&quot;  Yet is used to juxtapose the theory (of mages being the best soloers) and the reality (that mages cannot solo mobs from 0-5 levels below them), in order to lead the reader to the conclusion that <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> if</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> mages are supposed to be the best soloers (which the writer affirms they are), <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> then</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> they should be able to solo mobs of higher level than they currently do, i.e. mobs closer than 5 levels below, but not of higher level.  Since, persumably, no person who has played EQ past level 50 would agree to such a conclusion, I hope we can be done with this absurd semantic debate.  I thought it was concluded on page one.  I hope you're now satisfied?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Second, he is not a spokesperson for all the mages here, yet you treat him as one. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
No, I really don't.  That's why I'm addressing points made by other people on this thread.  You'll notice that Goladus and I had a civil and (I think) productive discussion about soloing mobs that summon and (I think) agreed that, to an extent, this <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> is</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> a strength of pet-class casters over non-pet-class casters.  We also agreed that the window of summoning mobs that can be soloed by a pet class is fairly small.<br>
<br>
I would never assume that mages as a whole would request some of the silly things that I see proposed on these boards from time to time (everything from make us melees to delete our class to give us wizard-powered nukes...), just as I wouldn't expect anyone reading the enchanter boards (God forbid) to assume that any one poster stands for all enchanters.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> You keep bringing up facts, and refuse to show any.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It's a funny thing about facts.  Sometimes, no matter how many different ways you articulate them, no matter to what efforts you go to express and demonstrate them, some recalcitrant people refuse to acknowledge their existence, much less their validity.<br>
<br>
So here are some facts, in no particular order.  For the most part, they are drawn from my earlier posts, but presented in numbered format for easier comprehension:  <br>
<br>
1.  It is a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> fact</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> that the ability to (consistently) solo level 55-60 creatures (while level 60, we'll say) would be incredibly damaging and unbalancing to EverQuest.<br>
<br>
2.  It is a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> fact</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> that classes with pets have certain soloing advantages versus monsters that summon, when compared to other pure casters that lack these pets.<br>
<br>
3.  It is a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> fact</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> that the Manna Robe is not a grossly overpowered mana regen tool for wizards with their epics.  Though it provides a roughly 10% increased return manawise, this diffence is readily recovered in 6 additional seconds of meditation that require no intervention by the player.<br>
<br>
4.  It is a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> fact</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> that Silverblade soloed shrooms in Fungus Grove at a rate of 1 shroom per 3-4 minutes, with a sustainable DPS of around 80.<br>
<br>
5.  It is a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> fact</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> that a well equipped wizard with 88 AA points can solo 4 blue mobs per 12 minutes.<br>
<br>
6.  It is a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> fact</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> that mages have strengths and weaknesses, as do all other classes.  It is, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> furthermore</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> fact</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> that these strengths and weaknesses are going to be judged versus the strengths and weaknesses of other classes in order to finalize caster balancing.<br>
<br>
7.  It is a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> fact</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> that mages are extremely effective damage dealers in normal experience group situations.<br>
<br>
8.  It is a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> fact</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> that to have one's suggestion about how to balance one's class taken seriously, it must be <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> reasonable</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and not a simple &quot;I want&quot; list.<br>
<br>
9.  It is a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> fact</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> that any direct upward scaling of magician power may threaten the relative power structure of the classes <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> not just for soloing</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> but in group environements as well, making some classes unduly unfavorable options in groups.<br>
<br>
10.  It is a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> fact</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> that the initial request of this thread was to scale magician power upwards, via direct modifications to the mage's powerset (charm / improved pets / snares / improved damage spells were specifically requested).<br>
-----<br>
<br>
You want to talk solo balancing?  Talk all you want.  I've made my point with regard to mage soloing, and pet-class soloing in general.<br>
<br>
There are advantages and disadvantages.  Personally, I'm not a big fan of the pet exp penalty thing myself, though, since I have Dire Charm, I too am a bit biased.  Pets allow us to do amazing things... things that non pet classes can't do but with great effort.  On the other hand, pets are liabilities of their own (no invis, pathing worries, lower level aggro worries, etc) at times.  Are they underpowered?  With the exception of the post-50 fire pets, I don't really think so.  Can they use some improvements to make them more attractive in raids?  Absolutely.  That's still where I think the major mage weaknesses are.  Additions to the burnout line to allow mage pets to benefit from non-mage haste buffs, while benefiting from burnout as well could make them more attractive.  As could bane weapons.  All sorts of things....<br>
<br>
But then again, what do I know?<br>
<br>
I'm just the enchanter.<br>
 <p>
Master Maldisdain Atheist<BR>
